import re
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Create an RDD by parallelizing a collection of text documents
documents = sc.parallelize([
    "Apache Spark is a unified analytics engine for big data processing, with built-in modules for SQL, streaming, machine learning and graph processing.",
    "Hadoop is an open-source software framework for storing data and running applications on clusters of commodity hardware.",
    "Python is an interpreted high-level programming language for general-purpose programming.",
    "Java is a class-based, object-oriented programming language that is designed to have as few implementation dependencies as possible.",
    "Scala is a general-purpose programming language providing support for functional programming and a strong static type system.",
    "R is a programming language and free software environment for statistical computing and graphics supported by the R Foundation for Statistical Computing.",
    "SQL is a domain-specific language used in programming and designed for managing data held in a relational database management system."
], 2)

def regex_func(line):
    return re.sub(r'\b\w{1,2}\b', '', line).replace("  ", "")

filtered_doc = documents.map(regex_func)
word_counts = filtered_doc.flatMap(lambda line: line.split(" ")) \
    .map(lambda word: (word, 1)) \
    .reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)

# Plot the bar chart
def plot_bar_chart(word_counts, title="Word Count Bar Plot", figsize=(8, 6)):
    words, counts = zip(*word_counts)
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    bars = plt.bar(words, counts)
    plt.xlabel('Words')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title(title)

    # Annotate occurrences on the bar plots
    for bar in bars:
        yval = bar.get_height()
        plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval, round(yval, 2), ha='center', va='bottom')

    # Rotate x-axis labels vertically
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)

    plt.show()

# After each line execution, collect and plot the bar chart
word_counts_data = word_counts.collect()
plot_bar_chart(word_counts_data, title="Word Count Bar Plot", figsize=(40, 6))

# Calculate the frequency of each word in the collection
total_count = word_counts.map(lambda x: x[1]).reduce(lambda a, b: a + b)
word_freq = word_counts.map(lambda x: (x[0], round(x[1] / total_count, 2)))

# Display the top N words with the highest frequency
N = 3
top_words = word_freq.takeOrdered(N, key=lambda x: -x[1])

for word, freq in top_words:
    print("{}: {:.2%}".format(word, freq))

import re
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Create an RDD by parallelizing a collection of text documents
documents = sc.parallelize([
    "Apache Spark is a unified analytics engine for big data processing, with built-in modules for SQL, streaming, machine learning and graph processing.",
    "Hadoop is an open-source software framework for storing data and running applications on clusters of commodity hardware.",
    "Python is an interpreted high-level programming language for general-purpose programming.",
    "Java is a class-based, object-oriented programming language that is designed to have as few implementation dependencies as possible.",
    "Scala is a general-purpose programming language providing support for functional programming and a strong static type system.",
    "R is a programming language and free software environment for statistical computing and graphics supported by the R Foundation for Statistical Computing.",
    "SQL is a domain-specific language used in programming and designed for managing data held in a relational database management system."
], 2)

def regex_func(line):
    return re.sub(r'\b\w{1,2}\b', '', line).replace("  ", "")

# Process each line separately and plot the bar chart after each line execution
for i, line in enumerate(documents.collect(), 1):
    print(f"Processing Line {i}: {line}")

    # Create RDD for the current line
    current_line_rdd = sc.parallelize([line], 1)

    # Apply regex function
    filtered_doc = current_line_rdd.map(regex_func)

    # Plot the bar chart after removing short words
    word_counts = filtered_doc.flatMap(lambda line: line.split(" ")) \
        .map(lambda word: (word, 1)) \
        .reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)

    word_counts_data = word_counts.collect()
    plot_bar_chart(word_counts_data, title=f"Word Count Bar Plot - Line {i}", figsize=(8, 6))

    # Calculate the frequency of each word in the collection
    total_count = word_counts.map(lambda x: x[1]).reduce(lambda a, b: a + b)
    word_freq = word_counts.map(lambda x: (x[0], round(x[1] / total_count, 2)))

    # Display the top N words with the highest frequency
    N =

    top_words = word_freq.takeOrdered(N, key=lambda x: -x[1])

    for word, freq in top_words:
        print("{}: {:.2%}".format(word, freq))

    # # Plot the bar chart for word frequency
    # plot_bar_chart(word_freq.collect(), title=f"Word Frequency Bar Plot - Line {i}", figsize=(8, 6))

    print('\n\n')

In [36]:
import re
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from tkinter import Tk, Label, Text, Button, Scrollbar, END

# Create an RDD by parallelizing a collection of text documents
documents = None  # Will be set after submitting the input

def regex_func(line):
    return re.sub(r'\b\w{1,2}\b', '', line).replace("  ", "")

def process_and_plot():
    input_text = input_text_widget.get("1.0", END)

    global documents
    documents = sc.parallelize(input_text.splitlines(), 2)

    # Clear the output text widget
    output_text_widget.delete("1.0", END)

    # Process each line separately and update the output text widget
    for i, line in enumerate(documents.collect(), 1):
        output_text_widget.insert(END, f"Processing Line {i}: {line}\n")

        # Create RDD for the current line
        current_line_rdd = sc.parallelize([line], 1)

        # Apply regex function
        filtered_doc = current_line_rdd.map(regex_func)

        # Plot the bar chart after removing short words
        word_counts = filtered_doc.flatMap(lambda line: line.split(" ")) \
            .map(lambda word: (word, 1)) \
            .reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)

        word_counts_data = word_counts.collect()
        plot_bar_chart(word_counts_data, title=f"Word Count Bar Plot - Line {i}", figsize=(8, 6))

        # Calculate the frequency of each word in the collection
        total_count = word_counts.map(lambda x: x[1]).reduce(lambda a, b: a + b)
        word_freq = word_counts.map(lambda x: (x[0], round(x[1] / total_count, 2)))

        # Display the top N words with the highest frequency
        N = 3
        top_words = word_freq.takeOrdered(N, key=lambda x: -x[1])

        for word, freq in top_words:
            output_text_widget.insert(END, "{}: {:.2%}\n".format(word, freq))

        # # Plot the bar chart for word frequency
        # plot_bar_chart(word_freq.collect(), title=f"Word Frequency Bar Plot - Line {i}", figsize=(8, 6))

def plot_bar_chart(word_counts, title="Word Count Bar Plot", figsize=(8, 6)):
    words, counts = zip(*word_counts)
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    bars = plt.bar(words, counts)
    plt.xlabel('Words')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title(title)

    # Annotate occurrences on the bar plots
    for bar in bars:
        yval = bar.get_height()
        plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval, round(yval, 2), ha='center', va='bottom')

    plt.show()

# Create the main window
root = Tk()
root.title("Word Processing UI")

# Create input text widget
input_text_widget = Text(root, height=10, width=50)
input_text_widget.pack(padx=10, pady=10)

# Create submit button
submit_button = Button(root, text="Submit", command=process_and_plot)
submit_button.pack(pady=10)

# Create output text widget with vertical scrollbar
output_text_widget = Text(root, height=20, width=50)
output_text_widget.pack(padx=10, pady=10)

scrollbar = Scrollbar(root, command=output_text_widget.yview)
scrollbar.pack(side="right", fill="y")

output_text_widget.config(yscrollcommand=scrollbar.set)

# Run the Tkinter event loop
root.mainloop()

from nbconvert import HTMLExporter
import nbformat

# Replace 'your_notebook.ipynb' with the actual name of your notebook
notebook_name = 'RDD_Streaming_DataVisualisation.ipynb'

# Read the notebook
with open(notebook_name, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as notebook_file:
    notebook_content = nbformat.read(notebook_file, as_version=4)

# Configure the HTML exporter
html_exporter = HTMLExporter()

# Convert notebook to HTML
html_output, resources = html_exporter.from_notebook_node(notebook_content)

# Save the HTML content to a file
html_file_name = notebook_name.replace('.ipynb', '.html')
with open(html_file_name, 'w', encoding='utf-8') as html_file:
    html_file.write(html_output)

print(f"HTML file '{html_file_name}' has been created.")
